WEBVTT

00:02.370 --> 00:10.180
A little while ago, somebody was expressing to me just how complex the immigration laws are in the United States.

00:11.401 --> 00:21.955
I'm not that familiar with immigration law in the United States, and so I was doing a little research and kind of looking this up to try to kind of grasp, well, what do they mean when they say it's super difficult?

00:22.856 --> 00:27.602
Well, I found a paper written by the Cato Institute, and in that paper there was a graphic.

00:28.258 --> 00:31.202
The graphics on the screen, you're not going to be able to read it.

00:31.422 --> 00:33.785
Even if you have it right up next to your face, it's pretty hard to read.

00:34.726 --> 00:43.857
But what they tried to do in this article was sort of flow chart out how the immigration process works in the United States.

00:44.618 --> 00:48.583
And I will confess, this is the simplified version of it.

00:49.244 --> 00:54.330
When I tried to follow all the stuff that was happening, I was like, well, this is hopelessly complex.

00:54.370 --> 00:55.812
Who can understand this stuff?

00:57.294 --> 00:57.714
Now,

00:58.338 --> 01:06.187
Granted, the Cato Institute is a libertarian organization, so I do think they have a bias in trying to show how complex something is.

01:06.667 --> 01:10.772
But still, nonetheless, seeing this, it feels overwhelming.

01:11.813 --> 01:23.826
I read in the same paper that the standard immigration law textbook is 2,656 pages long with 300 pages of footnotes

01:24.194 --> 01:33.024
on sort of legal cases and precedents and things that keep in mind as you try to navigate the immigration system in the United States.

01:33.965 --> 01:45.458
Now, while I was thinking about this, it sort of dawned on me for a lot of people I think Christianity can feel the same, especially to those who aren't newer to Christianity.

01:46.460 --> 01:50.524
I mean, we have a book, we have a Bible, it can feel overwhelming.

01:51.525 --> 01:52.146
There are

01:52.258 --> 01:56.204
31,102 verses in the Bible.

01:57.265 --> 02:01.912
Over 800,000 plus words depending on the translation.

02:02.693 --> 02:09.042
The one we have in the church and the racks in front of you, this is about a thousand pages of pretty small print.

02:10.203 --> 02:14.930
And if you were to take some of the things the Bible talks about them and lay them out on a map,

02:15.522 --> 02:29.961
Things like predestination and free will, the relationship of church and state, how divorce and remarriage happen, work, gender, money, those kinds of things, race and ethnicity, it would look pretty complex.

02:32.184 --> 02:42.738
But the interesting thing is the passage we're going to look at this morning in that God says, my commands are not burdensome.

02:45.602 --> 02:47.245
but they do sometimes feel burdensome.

02:48.166 --> 02:50.049
It feels like there's a lot of them.

02:50.069 --> 02:51.632
There's 66 books in here.

02:51.672 --> 02:52.753
There's a lot of verses.

02:53.795 --> 02:58.002
It feels like there's a lot of things God has to say, and some of the things seem difficult to do.

02:58.042 --> 03:02.248
Almost all of them feel very counter-cultural.

03:03.330 --> 03:13.266
And so what should we make of the idea that when God says, my commands are not burdensome, yet often the Bible and the word of God feels burdensome?

03:14.146 --> 03:23.062
You see, we've been talking about the importance of loving God and the best thing that we can do to love God in return for what He's done for us is to love others.

03:24.183 --> 03:26.107
Well, how do you know how to love someone else?

03:26.127 --> 03:27.850
Well, God says, I wrote it down for you.

03:28.952 --> 03:39.410
But the problem is if we think this is overwhelming, if we think this is intimidating, if we're like, I don't even know where to start, well, then how are we going to know how to love our neighbor?

03:40.386 --> 03:48.417
So this morning, we want to look at a passage in which God claims and says that His commands are not burdensome.

03:49.198 --> 04:10.226
And we want to try to understand how might we be thinking about the Bible and the commands of God wrongly when we do think they are burdensome and how this morning might we be able to think differently about God's Word so that we might recognize the truth of the grace that God gives us in the commands He has for us.

04:10.754 --> 04:16.503
So with that said, let me invite you to take a Bible and turn to the book of 1 John chapter 5.

04:17.344 --> 04:21.150
Like I said, there are Bibles in the seat in front of you and the rack in front of you.

04:21.911 --> 04:23.693
In those Bibles, it's page 988.

04:24.114 --> 04:28.461
So again, we're already near the thousand page mark.

04:29.222 --> 04:34.830
Here we are looking at a really long book, but we're in 1 John chapter 5 page 988.

04:35.191 --> 04:40.018
And we're going to think together about

04:40.450 --> 04:47.898
The Word of God, the commands of God to us today and what the Lord has to say about that.

04:47.918 --> 04:57.308
So 1 John 5, I'm going to read verses 1 to 4, page 988, 1 John 5.

05:01.333 --> 05:09.682
Everyone who believes that Jesus is the Christ is born of God and everyone who loves the Father loves his child as well.

05:10.626 --> 05:17.054
This is how we know that we love the children of God by loving God and carrying out His commands.

05:18.135 --> 05:21.459
In fact, this is love for God to keep His commands.

05:23.341 --> 05:27.607
And His commands are not burdensome.

05:28.608 --> 05:31.191
For everyone born of God overcomes the world.

05:31.832 --> 05:36.978
This is the victory that has overcome the world, even our faith.

05:38.146 --> 05:40.750
Now the logic of the passage is pretty straightforward.

05:41.851 --> 05:48.480
The first part of verse 1, God loves us and so He sent Jesus to be the Savior of the world.

05:50.303 --> 06:01.639
Second half of verse 1, we respond correctly to the love God has for us by loving His other children, by loving our neighbors, loving those that are in our lives.

06:03.161 --> 06:04.082
Verse 2,

06:05.090 --> 06:10.538
When we love others, how we do that is by doing the commands of God.

06:10.638 --> 06:15.966
God tells us, do these things, and this is how you will love your neighbor.

06:17.528 --> 06:27.082
Verse three, the first half of verse three, when we love our neighbor, we are not only loving our neighbor by obeying the commands of God, we're also loving God by doing that.

06:28.825 --> 06:32.530
And then comes the statement that might be considered slightly controversial.

06:33.732 --> 06:34.994
Second half of verse three.

06:35.906 --> 06:40.110
and his commands are not burdensome.

06:42.532 --> 06:45.795
What God tells us to do is not burdensome.

06:46.756 --> 06:49.399
And again, but you look and you're like, this is a pretty thick book.

06:50.700 --> 06:53.122
It can feel a little bit like immigration law.

06:54.243 --> 06:58.407
It can feel like there's a great flowchart in decision tree to try to figure things out.

06:59.428 --> 07:05.394
We can think, man, there's lots of stuff that God is saying, what do you mean it's not burdensome?

07:06.498 --> 07:19.711
Well, taking God in his word, when he says it's not burdensome, maybe when we think it is burdensome, we might be thinking about the Bible and thinking about the commands of God incorrectly.

07:21.032 --> 07:35.346
If we think of the Bible like the immigration laws in the United States, we're going to come away thinking it's burdensome, and so maybe that's the wrong way to think about

07:35.554 --> 07:36.475
the commands of God.

07:37.637 --> 07:50.256
So what I'd like to do this morning is offer four different ways, different than the immigration law, to think about God's word, four different metaphors.

07:50.296 --> 08:05.138
Now these are not mutually exclusive so we don't pick one over the other, but these are four different metaphors that we can use to help us think about the Bible and the word of God differently so that we might come to recognize that it is not.

08:05.410 --> 08:07.293
meant to be burdensome.

08:08.214 --> 08:15.704
Now, no metaphor is perfect, and these metaphors might seem a little sort of weird.

08:16.405 --> 08:25.057
Just in the sense of when you use a metaphor, you're trying to take things from everyday life and use them to help explain something that is complex.

08:25.678 --> 08:34.450
Well, the Bible, the Word of God, the commands of God are complex enough that we have four different metaphors this morning to try to help us shape

08:34.722 --> 08:42.812
a view of God's word whereby we can come to understand that it is not burdensome.

08:42.832 --> 08:46.476
So, let's start metaphor number one.

08:48.038 --> 08:53.105
What if we thought about the Bible like TurboTax software?

08:54.727 --> 08:58.772
It's the start of a new year, which means tax season is coming.

09:00.213 --> 09:04.018
Now, for some who are accountants, this might actually fill you with joy.

09:04.642 --> 09:06.445
or at least you're not intimidated by it.

09:07.206 --> 09:15.317
For the rest of us, it's overwhelming because the tax code is even more complex than the immigration code.

09:15.337 --> 09:18.241
And you try to figure out how do you find your way through this?

09:19.283 --> 09:20.244
Well, I don't know about you.

09:20.384 --> 09:23.048
I use tax prep software, and it's actually pretty helpful.

09:24.570 --> 09:25.712
You might use something different.

09:26.133 --> 09:32.722
TurboTax, one of the things I like about it is along the way, it's offering me these comforting statements like, hey,

09:32.930 --> 09:34.512
We're doing income right now.

09:35.013 --> 09:37.477
Don't worry about expenses, we'll get to that later.

09:38.138 --> 09:42.745
And I think to myself, oh good, the software knows when we're supposed to enter other numbers.

09:43.085 --> 09:45.549
All I gotta do is enter my income right now.

09:46.530 --> 09:51.698
There's also somebody that you can tax their call to be like, hey, I don't even have any idea what this is talking about.

09:51.718 --> 09:52.640
Can you help me with this?

09:54.563 --> 09:57.247
What have we thought about the Bible that way?

09:58.729 --> 10:02.194
What I mean is, although the whole Bible

10:03.010 --> 10:04.692
feels a little like the tax code.

10:05.513 --> 10:07.055
Like, wow, there's lots of stuff in here.

10:08.417 --> 10:16.308
In reality, when we're talking about the commands of God, God does not give us commands all at once.

10:17.089 --> 10:25.880
Meaning, it's not like he just kind of dropped the Bible into our world and was like, there's the book, learn it, know everything, you're responsible for all of it.

10:26.061 --> 10:27.583
Right now, there'll be a test tomorrow.

10:29.165 --> 10:30.226
That's not what he does.

10:31.170 --> 10:39.882
In fact, he functions a lot more like tax prep software in which sermons are only on one passage at a time.

10:41.124 --> 10:43.908
Bible reading is on one passage at a time.

10:44.328 --> 10:47.453
When you're going through a devotional, it's one passage at a time.

10:47.773 --> 10:54.402
In Bible study or in Sunday school, God does not give us all the commands all at once.

10:55.884 --> 10:58.188
That would be overwhelming.

10:58.208 --> 10:59.890
Instead, what he does is every Sunday,

11:00.834 --> 11:03.778
or Tuesday morning, or daily when you get up.

11:04.419 --> 11:09.586
He has some portion of the commands of God for us to focus on.

11:10.887 --> 11:14.973
This morning, we're in 1 John 5, 1 to 4.

11:16.074 --> 11:16.976
What about Leviticus?

11:17.556 --> 11:20.560
It's in there, but we're not worried about Leviticus right now.

11:21.422 --> 11:25.647
And you can think about the Spirit saying things like, don't worry about Leviticus.

11:25.687 --> 11:28.151
We're focused on 1 John 5 right now.

11:28.671 --> 11:30.674
We'll get to Leviticus later.

11:32.738 --> 11:38.368
In this way, the commands of God are not burdensome because He doesn't give them to us all at once.

11:39.531 --> 11:42.716
He says, this is what I have for you in this moment.

11:43.498 --> 11:45.381
This is what I want you to think about today.

11:45.822 --> 11:48.066
This is what I want you to focus on.

11:50.391 --> 11:51.312
Metaphor number two.

11:53.376 --> 11:56.562
Maybe we could think about the Bible like a concierge.

11:57.986 --> 12:13.002
Now you might think guidebook or trip advisor, whatever you want to say, when you go on a trip, when you go into a new place, if you go on a cruise or you go on a resort, if you go someplace you've never been before, often the hotel or the cruise ship or the resort will have a concierge.

12:13.662 --> 12:16.785
And the concierge's job is, look, you've not been here before.

12:17.686 --> 12:20.770
Let me explain to you what goes on in this place.

12:21.030 --> 12:22.591
Here's the fun things you should do.

12:22.932 --> 12:25.074
Here's some restaurants you might want to try.

12:25.538 --> 12:29.823
Here's an activity that maybe you've never done before or haven't done in a long time.

12:31.545 --> 12:34.909
Right now in Grand Rapids, most of us are probably not thinking about snorkeling.

12:37.192 --> 12:41.177
But if you go on a trip, the concierge is like, hey, look, the snorkeling's really great.

12:41.437 --> 12:42.598
Here's where you ought to go.

12:42.859 --> 12:44.020
This is how you should do it.

12:44.040 --> 12:45.342
You're going to really enjoy it.

12:48.606 --> 12:49.587
So it is with the Bible.

12:51.109 --> 12:52.210
In many ways,

12:52.354 --> 12:55.439
when we become Christians, we are entering a new world.

12:56.400 --> 12:59.385
It's still this world, but it's the world of eternal life.

13:00.366 --> 13:01.628
It's the kingdom of God.

13:02.630 --> 13:07.917
It's a realm in which Jesus is Lord and He is reigning and ruling over all things.

13:08.939 --> 13:13.586
Well, in this new realm, it's like going to a new vacation spot.

13:14.018 --> 13:18.565
And we need someone to sort of say, hey, look, in this new place, you ought to try these things.

13:18.885 --> 13:25.495
You may not be familiar with these activities because they weren't a part of your life before, but they can be a part of your life now.

13:26.036 --> 13:28.499
In that way, the Bible is like a concierge.

13:28.519 --> 13:40.036
It's like, hey, look, if you've never tried giving, if you've never known the joy of contributing financially to someone else and not just to yourself, you should try it.

13:40.096 --> 13:41.458
You're going to be blessed by it.

13:42.562 --> 13:44.424
The Bible also talks about fasting.

13:45.485 --> 13:51.031
Part of the purpose is fasting in the kingdom of, I mean fasting in the world is just for losing weight.

13:51.751 --> 13:55.675
In the kingdom of God, it actually turbocharges our prayer life.

13:56.256 --> 13:58.118
It gives real power to things.

13:59.139 --> 14:03.023
And so the Bible is like a concierge saying, hey, try this activity.

14:03.944 --> 14:06.066
You may not be familiar with it, but you're going to love it.

14:06.827 --> 14:09.970
It's powerful, it's hard, but it's powerful.

14:11.458 --> 14:15.083
which is the second reason why the commands of God are not burdensome.

14:16.866 --> 14:19.329
Is there introducing us to a world?

14:20.251 --> 14:28.823
And they're telling us activities that when we do those activities, we're going to experience the blessings of the world we're now a part of.

14:30.045 --> 14:33.650
A concierge is not meant to be burdensome, a concierge is meant to be helpful.

14:34.658 --> 14:41.949
You can ignore the concierge and kind of do whatever you want, but most people when they get to the end, they're like, oh man, there was so much stuff here, I just got overwhelmed by it all.

14:43.752 --> 14:45.194
So too, with the kingdom of God.

14:46.095 --> 14:52.705
The Bible is designed by God to say, hey, in this new world, try these activities.

14:53.867 --> 15:00.617
You're gonna find that they're gonna really make your time in the kingdom of God extremely beneficial.

15:02.460 --> 15:03.602
metaphor number three.

15:05.538 --> 15:08.001
The Bible is like a concert writer.

15:09.082 --> 15:13.227
What we mean by a concert writer is bands when they're going to stay at venues.

15:13.707 --> 15:20.575
They send a sort of contractor, a concert writer, which is like, look, this is what we expect to have happen when we get there.

15:21.016 --> 15:25.081
And in the writer, the band will spell out, this is what we think the stage is supposed to be like.

15:25.121 --> 15:27.023
This is what we want the sound equipment to work like.

15:27.243 --> 15:29.746
This is what our accommodations should be like.

15:30.882 --> 15:37.851
Now, one of the most famous examples of a concert writer is from a rock band from the 80s and early 90s called Van Halen.

15:39.393 --> 15:56.114
And in Van Halen's 53-page writer, they had a statement buried somewhere in the middle of the document that said that they wanted all the brown M&Ms removed from the giant bowl of M&Ms that they asked for in their dressing rooms.

15:57.314 --> 16:03.703
Now people gave him a super hard time for this because this looks like sort of rock star privilege like, are you too good to eat brown?

16:03.904 --> 16:05.246
I mean, they all taste the same anyway.

16:06.167 --> 16:09.873
Are you really going to make people go through and dig out all the brown M&Ms?

16:11.255 --> 16:14.900
Well, it turns out there was a rationale for what they were asking for.

16:15.701 --> 16:21.850
Apparently Van Halen had been on a tour and the technical specifications that they had put in their long rider had not been met.

16:22.551 --> 16:24.434
And so the tour went relatively poorly.

16:24.898 --> 16:34.290
So they came up with the idea of inserting the brown M&M clause in the middle of the rider because it gave them a very quick way when they walked into a venue.

16:34.350 --> 16:36.312
They immediately went to the bowl of M&Ms.

16:36.893 --> 16:45.564
If there were brown M&Ms in the bowl, they'd have to go upstairs and recheck all the technical connections because probably all of that stuff was wrong too.

16:47.246 --> 16:50.450
If they walked in and there were no brown M&Ms in the bowl,

16:50.658 --> 16:59.067
Then they could be confident that the venue had taken their request seriously, that they must have read the rest of the rider and done all of the stuff that's in that.

16:59.767 --> 17:05.553
And they could rest at ease that the technical specifications for their music was probably the way that they wanted them to be.

17:07.896 --> 17:09.177
The Bible is kind of similar.

17:10.338 --> 17:17.906
At first glance, you might think, well, the Bible is burdensome because there's all sorts of stuff kind of buried here and there.

17:18.242 --> 17:22.467
It's not like on page one, here are the most important five things to know.

17:23.809 --> 17:36.445
For example, there is one command in the Bible that explicitly states and very explicit worms that we're supposed to gather together regularly to meet for worship.

17:36.465 --> 17:40.050
Hebrews 10, 25, don't forsake the assembling of yourselves together.

17:41.090 --> 17:42.552
You might think, well, that's a little weird.

17:42.572 --> 17:44.095
Why not like say it more often?

17:44.135 --> 17:45.377
Or why not put it in the front?

17:45.417 --> 17:49.003
Or be like, here are the eight things you're supposed to know we're supposed to do.

17:49.023 --> 17:49.824
And why not put it there?

17:49.864 --> 17:50.765
That seems important.

17:52.588 --> 18:04.768
Well, the Bible is not burdensome because God has sort of buried things in different places because while the commands of God are not burdensome, they are serious.

18:06.631 --> 18:08.754
And the Lord is like, do you care?

18:09.954 --> 18:11.977
Do you care enough to find this stuff out?

18:12.918 --> 18:15.882
Do you care enough to seek after me with all your heart?

18:16.663 --> 18:28.379
And so he has buried some things in some obscure places or put some things in some strange places, not because he's trying to make it hard, but because he's trying to encourage us, look, this matters.

18:28.719 --> 18:29.620
This is serious.

18:29.961 --> 18:33.506
If you're going to take one verse seriously, then you'll take all the verses seriously.

18:36.490 --> 18:39.794
And it turns out that Hebrews 10, 25 is not the only time.

18:40.418 --> 18:42.481
that God says that we ought to gather together.

18:43.182 --> 19:00.385
He just says it in lots of different ways, and you don't find it until you see the one near the end of the Bible, actually, and begin to check out the fact that, oh, God's talking about this over and over again, all over the Scriptures.

19:00.405 --> 19:10.418
So the third reason, we might think the commands of God are burdensome, because important stuff seems to be buried all over the place, but they're not burdensome.

19:10.914 --> 19:19.464
It's just a sign of how seriously God takes our behavior and what he has going on for us in the kingdom of God.

19:20.766 --> 19:26.092
Metaphor number four, the Bible is like a note from your spouse.

19:27.994 --> 19:34.322
And I could have just said loved one, but that doesn't quite work because when you're married,

19:34.594 --> 19:39.160
there's a contractual vow sort of obligation you have to another person.

19:39.180 --> 19:45.668
Now, if you're not married, you can just sort of think about this as a note from a roommate, could be a note from a parent, could be a note from a friend.

19:46.148 --> 19:49.452
But I'm using the example of a note from a spouse.

19:49.472 --> 19:56.861
Suppose you wake up in the morning and there's a note on the countertop from your spouse and it says, can you please make sure you empty the dishwasher before you leave for work?

19:57.823 --> 20:00.626
Or it says, hey, look, can you make sure you finish dinner?

20:01.602 --> 20:06.910
Or it might say, hey, can you pick up our child from this practice at 4.30 today?

20:08.392 --> 20:10.935
Now, at first glance, you might think that's burdensome.

20:12.137 --> 20:14.540
This person is telling me something I got to do today.

20:16.263 --> 20:24.114
But in reality, it's not burdensome and it's not meant to be burdensome because you've made a vow to love this other person.

20:24.962 --> 20:32.591
And now here in kindness, this other person is saying, here's how you can love me today in very specific and tangible ways.

20:35.395 --> 20:39.099
So it is with God and the commands of God in his word.

20:40.261 --> 20:45.106
You might think, what does somebody give the God of the universe who has everything?

20:45.126 --> 20:46.448
I mean, how do you give him a present?

20:49.111 --> 20:50.733
Well, he spells it out pretty clearly.

20:50.773 --> 20:54.738
This is a note from him to say, hey, if you'd like to love me in return,

20:55.042 --> 21:02.472
If you're grateful for the stuff that I've done for you, here's some very tangible things you can do to show me love.

21:03.293 --> 21:10.103
So, for example, when you read in the Bible, remember the prisoner as if you are suffering with them.

21:10.503 --> 21:14.769
This is God writing you a note to say, hey, look, I love you.

21:14.829 --> 21:15.450
You love me.

21:15.510 --> 21:17.132
We have a relationship in Jesus.

21:17.453 --> 21:21.458
If you want to know how you can love me today, remember the prisoner.

21:22.018 --> 21:24.362
Write a note to a prisoner, pray for somebody in prison.

21:24.602 --> 21:28.188
Think about those who are in the justice system and how that's working.

21:28.449 --> 21:29.370
Pray for such people.

21:29.811 --> 21:36.703
That's God in his kindness, not meaning to be burdensome, but saying, look, you can't have a relationship if there's not love.

21:37.224 --> 21:39.207
How do we express love to God?

21:39.547 --> 21:42.192
God says, I'll tell you, here's a way you could do it.

21:42.673 --> 21:44.356
This would be meaningful to me.

21:46.078 --> 21:48.242
And so the commands of God are not burdensome.

21:49.314 --> 21:58.409
They do require something of us, but they're not burdensome because God is simply expressing to us.

21:59.992 --> 22:10.049
If you want to show me love, here's tangible, concrete, clear ways that you can show love to me by loving others.

22:12.413 --> 22:15.218
For metaphors, they're not mutually exclusive.

22:15.906 --> 22:20.272
They may be a little weird out there like, I thought you'd use like a sword or something, the kind of biblical metaphor.

22:21.294 --> 22:32.611
But the idea of metaphors is how could we think about the Bible and the commands of God differently or anew so that we might come to discover they are not burdensome.

22:34.033 --> 22:39.060
But although they're different metaphors, there is one thing that ties all four of them together.

22:41.364 --> 22:45.650
And that is there is a personal connection in all of the metaphors.

22:47.618 --> 22:49.660
See, we talked about the immigration code.

22:50.301 --> 22:53.225
The immigration code is super complex, but guess what?

22:53.265 --> 22:56.048
If you hire an immigration lawyer, that helps a lot.

